comments.text: That scan was created with a nextengine laser scanner, however I have had better luck recently using a david structured light scanner. I will be uploading some more artifacts in the near future that you can take a look at, but I highly recommend the sls-2 over the nextengine, the software is much more stable and you get quicker and higher quality results.
comments.author: need2

comments.text: Excellent, thanks! I've been using a MatterandForm scanner, which is fine for mid sized artifacts with less detail. Unfortunately it has been downright incapable of some smaller artifacts, finer details, and some types of stone. One last question, have you tried scanning anything with concave surfaces, glossy surfaces, or mesh surfaces (such as a hand woven basket)?
comments.author: nyersa

comments.text: Yes to all three. Glossy and translucent/transparent objects cause issues requiring surface treatment for all laser as well as structured light scanners. I have scanned baskets with it, they are challenging objects but it can be done. There are lots of tricks of course and a learning curve, but its totally doable.

I printed out the top and I was not able to fit my LCD into it. My printer is well calibrated and printed the part according to the dimensions in the STL. The problem is that the height of the LCD is an assembly of two boards. Depending on how your LCD panel was assembled at the factory, the dimension will vary. My LCD measured 91mm tall, which was 0.6mm taller than the space allowed. The space inside printed at 90.4mm. In my case, I should have stretched the height by 1% to make a comfortable fit. The width was close but it fit. My LCD measured 93mm wide and the print was 93.3mm inside. My rotary switch was not well centered in the hole. It was about 0.9mm right of center and 0.35mm higher. The other two switches were also right of center about the same amount. The first switch on the right measured about 11mm left of the right side of the LCD board. If you measure your LCD first, you will not have to print this twice to get it to fit.
Edit: In order to get the small knob to press fit well, I had to print it out at 101% and ream out the largest diameter hole with a 9/32" drill (102%)

Trapezoidal razor blade holder. Based on a design by paradiddle65 [ http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:36722 ]. The original design was well done, but had two small shortcomings. It was held together by a single large screw in the middle of the holder that allowed the ends to separate slightly. The tolerances used for the locking channels were too loose.
The following changes were made to the original design. Two small M3x16mm replaced the single large center screw. The locking channels were lengthened and held to tighter tolerances. The material reduction area was replaced with an internal blade storage compartment. The compartment can store up to five extra blades and still reduces the amount of filament required to print the holder. The holder was also widened to 15mm. This was done to accommodate the M3x16mm screws that were readily available.
NOTE: The locking channel tolerances are a little tighter than expected. A couple of light strokes with a small file on the edges will aided the initial assembly. With use, this issue resolves itself.

This is extremely simple, but very effective.  If the supporting edge of one of your plastic drawers is broken, the damaged portion often can be cut out and replaced with the simple piece I made.  It can then be sandwiched between two holey bars that can be bolted/riveted/wired together.  Cut and scale as your application dictates.  The parts may be holey but they are not sacred. :-)  I made holes for 3mm bolts.  Some might regard this as over-engineering a solution to a problem, but  I beg to differ.  There is duct tape involved!  Hopefully this does someone some good. :-) Enjoy!!!

More Eggbot plots.  pattern2-767.svg is the nicest of the three.  It was generated to be 1125 pixels high and then vertically shrunk to 66.667% of its original height.  That then gives an egg-suitable aspect ratio.
The other two plots, pattern2-800.svg and pattern2-1000.svg are, respectively, 800 and 1000 pixels high.  They are more appropriate for plotting on spheres as they have 1:1 aspect ratios.  The supplied Python program generates the 800 pixel high variant.  Change the HEIGHT variable setting for a 1000 pixel high plot.

The vertical components are in layer 1 while the horizontal components are in layer 2.  A top and bottom edge are in layer 3.  Plotting just layers 1 and 3 also makes for an nice egg. You can plot the entire design with the "Plot" tab of the Eggbot Control extension.  To plot layer-by-layer, use the "Layers" tab.
pattern2-767.svg has a fourth layer, "4 - test", which contains to small, horizontal tick marks.  You can plot just this layer to get the picture nicely framed on your egg.

title: Recreus Extruder Lever Type for OpenBuilds Mini-V Wheel Extrusion Carriage

description.text:
This is a lever type direct drive setup for the Recreus extruder. The lever allows quick replacement of filament without using tools. This unit can be used for stiff filament like ABS or PLA and for flexible filament like Recreus' FilaFlex. Soft filament requires less spring pressure for the lever than stiff filament, so, the body part has a deep hole for the spring to set in. With a plug filling part of the hole the tension can be increased, allowing the design to use one spring for different tensions for different types of filaments.
The lever uses a 608ZZ bearing held on a M5 bolt. The hole in the lever must be thread tapped for M5. The 4mm hole in the lever top assumes a 4mm OD x 3mm ID PTFE tube will be fitted in the hole to reduce wear on the hole and drag on the filament.
The mount is for an Open Builds Mini-V Wheel Plate. Sketchup files are included so other mountings can be easily designed.
The design is based off of the Recreus direct drive thing:263133.

Print with ABS. I used 40% infill. The hole in the bottom of the body must be tapped M6 for the Recreus barrel to be threaded into the body. You need a Bottom type tap as this is a blind hole. The hole in the lever needs to be tapped M5 for a 12mm long bolt to mount the 608ZZ bearing.
This is designed to be mounted on a Mini-V Wheel carriage running on a 20mm V-Slot extrusion by Open Builds. The mount can be modified for other mountings.
The assembled.skp file should be consulted for fitting pieces together.

description.text:
Water + Barley + Hops + Yeast = Beer (the beer being real beer dispensing from the faucet)
This tap handle represents the 4 main ingredients for beer.
I've included various versions of the handle to choose from. Icons can be printed separately and then glued into the handle. Instead of printing threading into the model, a threaded brass insert should be used.
Please check out the post about the build on my site:
http://fermware.com/3d-printed-tap-handles/

For best results, print the icons separately in appropriate colors then glue into the handle frame using your preferred method. Use a brass threaded insert made for plastic. The model available here has been designed for E-Z LOK 260-6-BR (3/8"-16 brass insert), which is available at McMaster in a 10 pack as 94615A118. The model is created with what I found to be an ideal 0.450" pilot hole, but you'll most likely need to clean up the printed hole with a 29/64" (0.453") drill bit. The McMaster recommended pilot hole is 7/16" (0.4375"), but you will definitely need to prep the hole with a generous amount of acetone to melt the ABS and press the bushing in carefully so you don't split the handle.
December 8, 2014 update:
I've uploaded a 2 part flask (shown in pictures). Print the outer (Flask_2part_flask) in clear and the inner (Flask_2part_yeast) in gold. I've got a dual extruder, so I printed them simultaneously. I can't say how printing the colors separately will turn out.

title: Screw & Nut Reference for Small Standard Sizes

description.text:
My first original published thing!
Pay attention to the instructions tab.
This thing is designed hold a nut and machine screw for #2-56, #4-40, #6-32, #8-32, #10-32 (fine thread #10) and 1/4"-20 as those are the most common standard sizes of small fasteners, and I blindly hate metric. Metric fasteners are also much more expensive than standard in the USA, often a couple of times the cost. #10-24 was omitted because I don't use it, and #12 was skipped because at that point you should be going up to the far cheaper and more widely available 1/4" coarse-thread hardware. The picture included is a roughout with el-cheapo Chinese ABS at .4mm resolution. It's still perfectly functional, but this can obviously be made quite prettier with better filament and resolution.

PAY ATTENTION TO THE UNITS ON THE FILE WHEN IMPORTING INTO REPETIER  
To use the original and tested model in Repetier, go to Config > Units of imported Objects > Inches. I have not tested the metric version, but provided a copy of it for those who think in those terms. The model is 7 1/2 inches long and should be able to barely fit on a 6x6 bed if turned 45 degrees. Make sure to print with the holes flat on the bed and numbers facing upwards.  
Install the nuts first on a flat surface using a hammer or rubber mallet. This worked with ABS, but YMMV for PLA. The holes are perfectly sized for starting the screws by hand and finishing with a screwdriver.

description.text: It's just a pawn.

I needed something to tilt my desktop music synths up at an angle, so that I didn't have to lean over them to see all the controls. Normally, I'd throw a chunk of wood under them, but I didn't have any suitable pieces. This foot is the result. You can see one of the first designs on the left in the photo. It looks like a cool little rocketship, but the STL was a mess, and it was too complicated for the purpose.
After a couple revisions, I settled on this design. It has a lip that will catch the rubber or plastic foot of the equipment it is placed under, so it doesn't slide out. The base is larger than the top for stability, and the general shape was chosen to reduce plastic required to build, and reduce print time.
Yes, this is a silly little thing, but I've now got six of them holding up the various gear in my studio!
Starting with a decently-well-tuned skeinforge, I set my skeinforge settings for two perimeter shells, and a 20% infill, and it worked great.

Hate warping and don't have a heated build platformâ€½ No worries, a few coins in perfboard will have you flat in no time. These are instructions for an UP!, but most tips should apply to a Cupcake too! YMMV. Taken from http://pp3dp.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=96&start=10#p1792, here's all you need to know about warp-free printing on the cheap! "The perfboard trick is baller! Big UP!s rross! I haven't had any warping since I started printing on it and I'm going deep and wide and tall. Of course I've done the platform leveling and nozzle height adjustments, but until I printed on perfboard, I'd get some warping on wide, long or thick prints. If you can't find copper plated perfboard, no worries; it's the holes, not the copper, that does the trick. A few tips if you decide to do this:
  • READJUST NOZZLE HEIGHT!!! Since you're adding ~1.5mm to the top of the platform, your current height will cause the nozzle to meet the perfboard in an unsightly way.
  • REMOVE! Remove the platform from the printer before attempting to dislodge the print from the perfboard. The print sticks well and you don't want to subject your printer to the forces necessary to to unstick it.
  • BIAS! Cut the board on an angle so that the perfs are not parallel to the printer's X and Y axes. I belatedly noticed that rross cut his on a bias; my utility knife scoring wasn't spot on, so it's all good. Yours will be better if you plan for this.
  • TAPE WELL! Ensure that the tape - blue painter's tape works great - sufficiently wraps around the top and bottom of the platform. On my first print, I wrapped the tape miserly on the perfboard and while printing, one of the strips detached. No prints suffered during this episode.
  • COOL! Definitely allow the platform to cool a few minutes before removing the print. The plastic in the holes contracts and makes removal easier.
  • DON'T PREHEAT! One of the bonuses of printing on perfboard is that the platform doesn't need preheating. This saves time, effort and watts.
  • OVERLAP! When printing multiple models, I overlap the rafts a bit so that all rafts are connected. This ensures that raft areas that fall outside the perfs are still secured by those that do (maybe less of any issue if you cut the board on a bias).
  • LED! Most of the plastic comes out of the holes, but to remove the bits that remain, LED leads work great (we all have the odd LED laying about, yes?)!"

Obtain Verboard or 0.1" fiberglass perfboard and cut to size at an angle. Semi-copper plated perfboard works best but the flatness is achieved mechanically, so don't sweat if you can't find the copper stuff.

This is a rehash of PhysicsDude's low-poly Fennec Fox but with column/tree type support which is both necessary and much easier to remove than other types of support. The STL is manifold and should play well with most slicers. :-) The column-tree support is done with Meshmixer. Share and Enjoy!! Having released V2 which printed nicely on my machine and later V3 which I have yet to print, it is clear that careful judgement is necessary when printing with support. Firstly, I'm a big fan of printing with fat brims on the 1st layer and I keep my acceleration low which leads to much smoother motion and less jerking about which helps with the survival of print jobs and their support structure. Here are the latest Meshmixer support structure generating settings incase someone wants to review them, tweak or comment. Regardless it is best to become familiar with the meaning of each of them for future support print jobs. General Settings:
Angle Thresh = 35
Contact Tol = 0
Y-Offset = 0 mm <--- Great to increase to raise up a project and deal with support removal rather than flatness of "bottom printing" Support Generator
Max Angle = 45
Density = 75
Layer Height = 0.4 mm (I usually print at 0.4mm and it reduces the polygon count)
Post Diameter = 3 mm
Tip Diameter = 0.8 mm
Base Diameter = 10 mm <-- could go as high as 40 here to create a nice mat below the project for good adhesion to the print surface (using a wide brim while slicing does the job too) Advanced Support:
Allow Top Connections = no (unchecked)
Optimization = 100 <-- Why not?
Solid Min Offset = 0
Tip Layers = 10 <-- Unusually Tall, allowing for some distance between the mass of structural support and the print project
Base Layers = 1 <-- This allows for a nice flat flexible "pancake" for adhesion
Strut Density = 50 <-- This is a matter of personal choice.
Post Sides = 16 In meshmixer you can also add and remove (ctrl-click) support structures to you heart's content. (its fun too) I hope this does someone else some good. Being able to print with support with confidence is a wonderful thing. :-)

comments.text: I'm sorry to hear that you had trouble.  The intent was to make things easy.  I"m not sure what you are printing with or at what speed.  Speed can be trouble at times and so can too low of a flow rate.  The structures are only 3mm wide and any deficiency there can have bad consequences.  Regardless, I'd strongly recommend playing with and mastering meshmixer's support generating tool.  Its free and powerful and I'd guess that if you put a dozen 3d printing fans in a room together, you would get a dozen different "ideal" understructure designs, one from each of them.  I personally print with a relatively low maximum acceleration and so my print jobs finish a little later but the job and printer don't get so much whipping around.  Whaterver you do, keep makin' stuff. :-)
